findings.title: Privilege Escalation: Self-Elevation to Admin
findings.description: User successfully set their own isAdmin flag to true
findings.remediation: Prevent modification of privilege fields in Firestore rules OR use Custom Claims

findings.title: Privilege Escalation: Self-Elevation to Owner
findings.description: User successfully set their own isOwner flag to true
findings.remediation: Prevent modification of privilege fields in Firestore rules

findings.title: Overly Permissive Default Rules
findings.description: Firestore rules may have a wildcard match that allows access to any collection.
findings.remediation: Avoid match /{document=**} with permissive rules. Define explicit rules for each collection.

findings.title: Unauthenticated Read Access to Private Messages
findings.description: Private messages are readable without authentication.
findings.remediation: Messages must require authentication: allow read: if request.auth != null

findings.title: IDOR Vulnerability on Private Data Collection
findings.description: Private user data is accessible by manipulating document IDs.
findings.remediation: Ensure document ID matches auth UID: allow read: if request.auth.uid == userId
findings._fingerprintSource: cwe:CWE-639||cat:A01||title:idor vulnerability on private data collection

findings.title: Sensitive Configuration Data Accessible
findings.description: API keys or other sensitive configuration stored in Firestore is accessible to regular users.
findings.remediation: Sensitive config should not be in client-accessible Firestore. Use Cloud Functions or secure backend storage.

findings.title: User Enumeration via Collection Listing
findings.description: Unauthenticated users can list/enumerate user documents, exposing user data.
findings.remediation: Prevent listing: require authentication and consider restricting list queries

findings.title: Subcollection Permission Bypass
findings.description: Subcollections may have different (weaker) permissions than their parent documents.
findings.remediation: Ensure subcollections have explicit rules: match /users/{userId}/private_notes/{noteId}

findings.title: Unrestricted Read Access
findings.description: Rule allows anyone to read data without authentication
findings.remediation: Change to: allow read: if request.auth != null
findings._fingerprintSource: cwe:CWE-284||cat:A01||loc:rule:allow read: if true||vuln:rule:allow read: if true||title:unrestricted read access

findings.title: Message Injection Possible
findings.description: Message creation does not validate that sender is in participants list
findings.remediation: Add: && request.auth.uid in request.resource.data.participants && request.resource.data.senderId == request.auth.uid

findings.title: Unauthenticated Read Access to User Data
findings.description: Firestore rules allow unauthenticated users to read user documents. This exposes potentially sensitive user information to anyone.
findings.remediation: Add authentication check: allow read: if request.auth != null

findings.title: Improper Access Control: Unauthenticated User Data Access
findings.description: 3 user profiles readable without authentication
findings.remediation: Change to: allow read: if request.auth != null
findings._fingerprintSource: cwe:CWE-284||cat:A01||title:improper access control: unauthenticated user data access

findings.title: IDOR Vulnerability on User Profiles
findings.description: Users can access other users' profiles by simply changing the document ID in the request.

evidence.detail: alice123 accessed bob456's profile by changing document ID

findings.remediation: Restrict reads to own profile: allow read: if request.auth.uid == userId

findings.title: Group Messages Exposed to Non-Members
findings.description: Users can read messages from groups they are not members of.

evidence.detail: alice123 read messages from private-group without membership

findings.remediation: Verify group membership before allowing access to group resources

findings.title: Missing Authorization on Admin Collection
findings.description: Admin-only collections are accessible without admin role verification.
findings.remediation: Add admin check: allow read: if get(/databases/$(database)/documents/users/$(request.auth.uid)).data.isAdmin == true

findings.title: Incorrect Authorization on Message Access
findings.description: Users can read messages without being a participant in the conversation.

evidence.detail: alice123 read message where she is not a participant

findings.remediation: Add participant check: allow read: if request.auth.uid in resource.data.participants

findings.title: Exposure of Private Personal Information
findings.description: Other users' PII accessible: email, friends
findings.remediation: Implement field-level access control or separate public/private profile data

findings.title: Content Security Policy (CSP) Header Not Set
findings.description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

findings.title: X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing
findings.description: The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.

These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page — covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.
